      &lt;dt id=&quot;package&quot;&gt;Package&lt;/dt&gt;
      &lt;dd&gt;
        
        
        &lt;a href=&quot;/packages/dnp3times.html&quot;&gt;dnp3times&lt;/a&gt;
          (&lt;a href=&quot;https://crates.io/crates/dnp3times&quot;&gt;crates.io&lt;/a&gt;)
        
        
      &lt;/dd&gt;

      &lt;dt id=&quot;type&quot;&gt;Type&lt;/dt&gt;
      &lt;dd&gt;
        
        Vulnerability
        
      &lt;/dd&gt;

      

      

      

      

      

      
      

      &lt;dt id=&quot;patched&quot;&gt;Patched&lt;/dt&gt;
      &lt;dd&gt;
        
        no patched versions
        
      &lt;/dd&gt;

      

      
      
    &lt;/dl&gt;

    
    

    &lt;h3 id=&quot;description&quot;&gt;Description&lt;/h3&gt;
    &lt;p&gt;The &lt;code&gt;dnp3times&lt;/code&gt; crate attempted to exfiltrate &lt;code&gt;.env&lt;/code&gt; files to a server
that was in turn impersonating the legitimate &lt;code&gt;timeapi.io&lt;/code&gt; service. It was
loosely trying to typosquat the &lt;code&gt;dnp3time&lt;/code&gt; crate, but otherwise was the same
attack as the &lt;code&gt;time_calibrator&lt;/code&gt; and &lt;code&gt;time_calibrators&lt;/code&gt; malware yesterday.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The malicious crate had 1 version published on 2026-03-04 approximately 6 hours
before removal and had no evidence of actual downloads. There were no crates
depending on this crate on crates.io.&lt;/p&gt;


